@flexiarg t3/com-b-convergence
@title COM-B Convergence
@sigils [📊/合]
@audience implementation-researchers, programme-evaluators, funders
@tone formal-analytic
@style design-pattern
@part Open Research Training
@up t3/transformation-space
@see t3/architectural-pair, t3/implementation-modes
@next t3/participatory-evaluation
@length 180-260
@allow-new-claims false

! conclusion:
  Quantitative COM-B survey data (T3 immediate n=52, T3 six-month follow-up n=7, T1 recipient baseline n=15) converge with the qualitative NPT findings: trainers report high motivation and perceived value (M>5.3) but consistently low institutional support for measuring effects (M=3.35), removing obstacles to uptake (M=3.38), and sustaining delivery (M=3.78). The bottleneck is not capability or motivation but opportunity — specifically, the institutional opportunity structures that would convert individual readiness into collective practice.

  + context: Qualitative findings identified architectural deficits through focus group analysis; quantitative data from COM-B-aligned Likert surveys provide independent triangulation.
  + if: You want to confirm that the qualitative patterns are not artefacts of sampling or interpretation.
  + however: Survey response rates are low (especially n=7 for the six-month follow-up); quantitative findings are directional and triangulating, not inferential.
  + then: Use the COM-B profile diagnostically: motivation and capability are not the intervention targets; institutional opportunity is. Design programme improvements that target the weakest COM-B component rather than reinforcing what is already strong.
  + because: When motivation is high and institutional infrastructure is low, adding more motivation-focused interventions (inspirational talks, value messaging) wastes resources; the leverage point is opportunity.
      + mechanism: COM-B identifies the binding constraint; NPT explains the social processes through which that constraint operates.
      + counterfactual: If we interpret high motivation as programme success and stop there, we miss the architectural deficit that prevents motivation from translating into practice.
      + applies-when: A programme has both qualitative and quantitative evaluation data and wants to integrate them.
      + does-not-apply: Purely qualitative studies or programmes without COM-B-aligned instruments.
      + signals: Survey items on value and motivation score high; survey items on institutional support and measurement score low; the gap is persistent across survey waves.
      + evidence: T3 immediate (n=52): "I see the value" M=5.37, "effects are being measured" M=3.35; T3 follow-up (n=7): motivation items increase, institutional items static; T1 (n=15): same pattern — value high, effort distribution and measurement low.
  + next-steps:
      - Present the COM-B profile to programme stakeholders as a diagnostic, not a scorecard.
      - Target interventions at the weakest component (institutional opportunity), not the strongest (motivation).
      - Repeat the survey after architectural interventions to test whether the profile shifts.
  + governance:
      - practice: include COM-B profiling in each evaluation cycle.
      - metric: change in the gap between motivation and opportunity scores over time.
